result.execSummary:
The defendant Me Lar Htoo was found guilty of the following charge(s) in this case.

  • Bail Jumping-Felony, a class H felony, Wisconsin Statutes 946.49(1)(b).

Charge(s) in this case were read in to this or other case(s). A "read in" charge is a charge that is dismissed as part of a plea agreement, however:

  • The defendant agrees to have the court consider the charge(s) when sentencing for another crime, under Wis. Stats. 973.20(1g)(b); and
  • The defendant cannot be prosecuted for these charge(s) in the future.

Notice to employers: It may be a violation of state law to discriminate against a job applicant because of an arrest or conviction record. Generally speaking, an employer may refuse to hire an applicant on the basis of a conviction only if the circumstances of the conviction substantially relate to the particular job. For more information, see Wisconsin Statute 111.335 and the Department of Workforce Development's publication, Arrest and Conviction Records under the Law.

3:41 PM; Case called for Plea/sentencing hearing.  Defendant Me Lar Htoo appeared by Zoom video, in custody at DCI.  Attorney Priya Barnes appeared by video for Me Lar Htoo.  Prosecuting attorney Peter Michael Tempelis in court for the State of Wisconsin. All parties have agreed that some may have the hearing conducted remotely. This hearing has met the statutory standards for video conferencing. Court notes this matter is a Branch 10 case but was set for plea and sentencing before this Branch by agreement of the parties.  Court inquires how the matter is proceeding today.  Atty. Barnes advises parties are prepared to resolve the matter today.  Court notes there is no plea questionnaire in the file.  Atty. Barnes apologizes as she thought she had previously filed the plea questionnaire, and files it with the court now.  Court has received the plea questionnaire and recites the offer.  State and Defense confirm the offer.  Court conducts plea colloquy with the defendant.

Based on the colloquy thus far the court is not comfortable with proceeding today.  Court notes the defendant advised he did not review the plea questionnaire with his attorney and this court is having issues with hearing the defendant and the defendant responding to its questions.  Court will adjourn the matter for status before Branch 10 to allow time for counsel to review the plea questionnaire with the defendant and for the Branch assigned to decide if it will allow Zoom appearance for plea and sentencing or have the defendant produced.
Hearing scheduled for October 31, 2022 at 09:00 am.
